  "id": "fun2-materials",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "fun2-materials.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "",
  "title": "Equations of Lines, Planes and Surfaces",
  "body": " Equations of Lines, Planes and Surfaces   FUN-2 Reading    Things you should understand and know:  Lines in three-dimensional space  Distance in three-dimensions  Planes in three-dimensions  The main features of ellipsoids, paraboloids, and hyperboloids  The traces of quadric surfaces and how to form a surface from them  The cylindrical coordinate system and how to locate points  The spherical coordinate system and how to locate points   Things you should be able to do:  Write the equation of a line in vector, parametric, and symmetric form  Find the distance between a point to a line  Write the equation of a plane in vector and scalar forms  Find the distance between a point and a plane  find the angle between two planes  Identify and sketch cylinders  Identify and sketch ellipsoids, paraboloids, and hyperboloids  Find the equations of traces  Use traces to sketch a quadric surface  Convert between rectangular, cylindrical, and spherical coordinates    You will be assessed on the following criteria:  Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps that follow progressively from one to the next.  Equations of Lines and Planes: Write and interpret the equations of lines and planes in various forms (vector, parametric, symmetric, scalar).  Calculating Distances and Angles: Calculate distances between points, lines, and planes, as well as angles between vectors and planes.  Quadric Surfaces: Finding traces in two dimensions and sketching quadric surfaces in three dimensions. Identifying the surface type from its equation.  Change of Coordinates: Convert between different coordinate systems (polar, cylindrical, spherical) and understand the relationship between them.      All of the readings for this course come from the OpenStax Calculus Volume 3 textbook, which is available for free online at https:\/\/openstax.org\/details\/books\/calculus-volume-3 . You can read the textbook online or download a PDF version. The textbook is also available in print from various retailers if you prefer a physical copy.  For this lesson, you should read sections 2.5 Equations of Lines and Planes in Space , 2.6 Quadric Surfaces , and 2.7 Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates .. You should read through the sections carefully, making sure to understand the definitions, examples, and key ideas. You should also work through the exercises at the end of each section to test your understanding and practice applying the concepts. Some of the exercises at the end of the section are assigned in the WP assignments.    FUN-2 Videos   Equations of Lines and Planes   Quadric Surfaces   Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates      FUN-2 Written Practice    INFORMATION ABOUT ALL WRITTEN PRACTICE (WP) ASSIGNMENTS:  All of the WP problems come from our online textbook: https:\/\/openstax.org\/details\/books\/calculus-volume-3  Complete solutions to all WP assignments can be found in Canvas within the section Module.  Links to the text and PDFs of the text can be found in the Canvas module under the Reading and Information.   THE WP ASSIGNMENTS ARE DESIGNED TO PREPARE YOU FOR THE QUIZZES AND ASSESSMENTS  Work on every problem on every assignment.  If you get stuck or do not understand a solution, ask questions.  For each problem, try it once or twice before looking at solutions or asking for help.  Mark the problems you did correctly on the first try.  Highlight problems where you got help (using solutions, videos, a tutor, etc) -These are the problem types that you will need more practice on to be ready for the assessments.  Understand that just copying the solutions instead of working through the problems will greatly reduce your chances of success in this class.   WP3 and WP4  Equations of Lines and Planes: Complete problems 247, 251, 257, 269, 271, 279, 285  Quadric Surfaces: Complete problems 313-318, 323, 327, 339, 345  Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates: Complete problems 363, 369, 387, 391, 399, 401, 405, 409, 411, 413  In addition to these problems, on separate paper complete the following exploration. This link Intersection of Planes will take you to the exploration. On the right side of the screen, you will be given some instructions and questions to answer. Follow the instructions and write out your answers to each of the questions. Don't forget to give the equation...!  WP3 Solutions  WP4 Solutions      FUN-2 Sample Outcomes   For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 50 minutes to complete 4 problems. Here are samples of the types of problems you will encounter:      Give the equation for the line passing through the point (4,-1,5) and in the direction orthogonal to the plane with equation . Give the parametric, symmetric, and vector equations.   To find the equation of a line in 3D space, you need a point on the line and a direction vector. The direction vector should be orthogonal to the given plane.  Parametric:  Symmetric:  Vector:    First, we find the normal vector to the plane , which is . This vector is orthogonal to the plane and can be used as the direction vector for the line.  Using the point (4, -1, 5) and the direction vector , we can write the parametric equations as:  , ,  The symmetric equations are:   The vector equation is:       Find the equation of the plane that passes through the points (2,0,4), (1,3,5), and (2,-1,0).   To find the equation of a plane through three points, you can use the cross product of two vectors formed by the points to find the normal vector.  Plane:  We first find two vectors in the plane:    The normal vector is:   The equation of the plane is:   Simplifying:       A plane is given by the equation 3x-2y+x=4.   Find the equation of a plane parallel to the given plane that passes through the point (-2,5,3).  Parallel planes have the same normal vector.   The normal vector to the given plane is . Since the new plane is parallel to the given plane, it has the same normal vector. Using the point (-2,5,3) and the normal vector , the equation of the new plane is:   Simplifying:    Therefore, the equation of the new plane is:      Find the angle between the given plane and the xy-coordinate plane. Give an exact simplified answer.  To find the angle between two planes, you can use the dot product of their normal vectors.   The normal vector to the given plane is . The normal vector to the xy-coordinate plane is . The angle between the planes is:   Therefore,       Identify the surface given by       The equation can be rewritten as . This is the equation of an elliptic paraboloid opening downward with vertex at (0,0,16).      Identify the surface given by     Elliptic Cylinder     The equation can be rewritten as . This is the equation of an elliptic cylinder opening along the x-axis with semi-axes of length 3 and 1.     Given .    Rewrite the equation in standard form.   To find the standard form, complete the square for each variable, then simplify the equation.    First we can get the like variables together:   We then need to factor out the leading coefficient for each set of variables:  Completing the square for each variable, we add the constants:   Then we can rewrite the equation as:       Identify the surface and the axis.   This is a hyperbolic paraboloid with the axis along the y-axis.      "
